{ Sorry I lied, there is one last thing you need to know before the fun begins!

This is how files will look in the move trainer tab. You have the option to click around the moves and see what you are about to train. Remember that this mode is optimized for drills, so in case you want a clearer overview of the whole repertoire, make sure to study using the reading mode.

Now that you were patient and followed my instructions, it's time to reward you with your first drill. Look behind the board and press the drill 'with arrows' button. } { [%csl Gd2] }
1. d4 Nf6 { [%cal Gb1c3] } 2. Nc3 g6 { [%cal Ge2e4] } 3. e4 { It's critical to understand that if Black doesn't put a pawn in the center with 3...d5, we can no longer play our lovely Jobava London.
<br>
The good news is that whenever Black goes for a strange opening in his own third, you can always apply the same developing scheme with f3-Be3-Qd2-0-0-0-g4-h4 and storm on the kingside. } 3... d6 4. f3 { Important to start with f3 before 4.Be3 because 4...Ng4 ideas can be pretty annoying to deal with. } 4... Bg7 { [%csl Gc1] } 5. Be3 O-O { [%csl Gd1] } 6. Qd2 Nbd7 7. O-O-O { Many players make the mistake of rushing with 7.Bh6, breaking a fundamental rule:
-we don't start concrete actions before castling } 7... b6 8. Bh6 { Important to do this first because 8.h4 allows Black to play 8...h5! and it becomes much more difficult to break on the kingside. } 8... Bb7 9. h4! { For the same reason we avoid the immediate trade of bishops as that would again...allow our opponent to meet 9.Bxg7 Kxg7 10.h4 with the annoying 10...h5!
<br>
The funny part about this attack is that you can ignore developing the f1-bishop and the g1-knight simply because they don't have an impactful square. This doesn't make them bad pieces by any means...they are just waiting for a convinient moment to make their presence felt. } 9... a5 10. h5 $40 *


